Cheat sheet

# Getting elements, inputs / buttons
// input here is the type of the HTML element
// so when I want to select an input field, I use 'input'
// and when I want to select a button, I use 'button'

// By placeholder text
cy.get('input[placeholder="Username"]')
cy.get('input[placeholder="Password"]')

// By ID
cy.get("#username").type("username");
cy.get("#password").type("DemoUserPassword!$$"); // Unique password unlikely to be in breach database

// By name attribute
cy.get('input[name="username"]').type("myusername");
cy.get('input[name="password"]').type("mypassword");

// By type
cy.get('button[type="submit"]').click();

.its() // requires that the property you're asking about exists on the object.

# Chaining from a cy.get()
cy.get('textarea.post-body').type('This is an excellent post.')

Here are even more action commands Cypress provides to interact with your app:

.blur() - Make a focused DOM element blur.
.focus() - Focus on a DOM element.
.clear() - Clear the value of an input or textarea.
.check() - Check checkbox(es) or radio(s).
.uncheck() - Uncheck checkbox(es).
.select() - Select an <option> within a <select>.
.dblclick() - Double-click a DOM element.
.rightclick() - Right-click a DOM element.

# Cypress assertions
cy.get(':checkbox').should('be.disabled') // This uses jquery selector to get all checkboxes, see below for more jquery examples
cy.get('form').should('have.class', 'form-horizontal')
cy.get('input').should('not.have.value', 'US')

You can chain multiple assertions together using .and(), which is another name for .should() that makes things more readable:

cy.get('#header a')
  .should('have.class', 'active')
  .and('have.attr', 'href', '/users')

# Changing the default timeout of the order

// ðŸš¨ DOES NOT WORK
cy.get('.selector').should('be.visible', { timeout: 1000 })
// âœ… THE CORRECT WAY
cy.get('.selector', { timeout: 1000 }).should('be.visible')

# Cypress jquery selectors

// Form element selectors
cy.get(':checkbox')    // All checkboxes
cy.get(':radio')       // All radio buttons
cy.get(':text')        // All text inputs
cy.get(':password')    // All password inputs
cy.get(':submit')      // All submit buttons
cy.get(':button')      // All buttons
cy.get(':input')       // All input, textarea, select, button elements

// State selectors
cy.get(':checked')     // All checked checkboxes/radios
cy.get(':selected')    // All selected options in <select>
cy.get(':disabled')    // All disabled elements
cy.get(':enabled')     // All enabled elements
cy.get(':visible')     // All visible elements
cy.get(':hidden')      // All hidden elements

// Positional
cy.get('li:first')     // First <li>
cy.get('li:last')      // Last <li>
cy.get('li:even')      // Even <li> elements
cy.get('li:odd')       // Odd <li> elements

# Cypress assertions for empty elements

// Check if element is empty (no children, no text)
cy.get('.cart-items').should('be.empty');

// Check if text is empty
cy.get('.cart-count').should('have.text', '');

// Check if element doesn't exist at all
cy.get('.cart-item').should('not.exist');

// Check if element has no children
cy.get('.book-list').children().should('have.length', 0);

// Check if value is empty (for inputs)
cy.get('input').should('have.value', '');

# Testing empty contains
cy.contains('Error message').should('not.exist');


# Testing MUI icons
Getting by aria-label

<IconButton aria-label="remove from cart" onClick={onRemove}>
  <Delete />
</IconButton>

cy.get('button[aria-label="remove from cart"]').first()..should('have.text', '');

# Searching for elements within others
Why: .contains() narrows down to the specific element with that text. When you called .within() on it, you were only searching inside that Typography element, not the whole drawer.
cy.get('[aria-label="cart count icon"]').find('.MuiBadge-badge').should('have.text', '0');

// OR use .within()
cy.get('[aria-label="cart count icon"]').within(() => {
  cy.get('.MuiBadge-badge').should('have.text', '0');
});


# Info why using MUI class names is a bad idea
1. version changes
2. In production builds, MUI generates classes like .css-1h9z7r5-MuiCard-root with random hashes. Your .MuiCard-root selector won't work.
3. its testing implementation details, if Mui changes, your tests break, even if your app still works
4. becomes brittle, if you switch styling it can break